    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Leave the expression in its most simplified form. If it can't get simplified rewrite the original expression.</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts_inline">
<li>\(\displaystyle{{@a1@}}\)</li>
<li>\(\displaystyle{{@a2@}}\)</li>
</ol>

<p>When simplifying remember only common factors can be cancelled.</p>

<h4 class="HELM_solution">Solution</h4>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</li>
<li>[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li>In the expression \(\displaystyle{{@a1@}}\), the term \(\displaystyle{{@b1@}}\) is common to both the numerator and the denominator and hence we have
<p>\(\displaystyle{{@a1@}} = \displaystyle{{@ta1@}}\)</p>
</li><li>In the expression \(\displaystyle{{@a2@}}\) notice that an \(a\) and \({@b2@}\) appear in both numerator and denominator. 
<p>However \(a\) and \({@b2@}\) are not common factors. Recall that factors of an expression are multiplied together whereas in the denominator \(a\) is added to \({@b2@}\). This expression cannot be simplified.</p>
</li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
